sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K864003
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Low copy BioBrick standard vector
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Erik Lundin
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: pSB4A15 is a BioBrick standard vector with low copy pSC101 replication origin (~5 copies per cell) and ampicillin antibiotic resistance marker, especially usable for Lambda Red recombineering in E coli. The backbone sequence is based on pSB3T5, but the E coli His operon terminator BBa_B0053 has been replaced with the late terminator of the Salmonella phage P22.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: The resistance cassette is terminated by a Lux bidirectional terminator. Adjacent to this terminator there is a designed primer binding site to where the forward primer for lambda red can be designed to bind to no matter what the insert in the cloning site is or what the resistance is. The resistance cassette is flanked by SalI and SacI restriction sites for easy switching of resistance in the backbone. The pSC101 origin of replication is flaked by NheI and MluI restriction sites for easy switching of origin of replication.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: pSB2K4
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: pSB2K3-derived BioBrick plasmid free of many restriction sites
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Austin Che, Leon Chan and Sri Kosuri
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Derived from pSB2K3 with many restriction enzyme sites removed by site-directed mutagenesis (~2 dozen mutations). Plasmid is useful when there is a need to cut with a variety of different restriction enzymes. Most symmetric cutters have been removed, and some non-symmetric cutters have also including AarI, AcuI, BbsI, BbvCI, BciVI, BsaI, BsmBI, EarI, N.BstNBI, and SgrAI. Works in exactly same way as pSB2K3. See <bb_part>pSB2K3</bb_part> for more information. Note that the VF2 site has a single base mutation in the middle of it. However, VF2 has been used successfully as a primer for PCR with this plasmid.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_J179000
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: pBS1C: Bacillus subtilis vector, amyE integration, CAM-resistance
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Jara Radeck
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
This vector integrates into the amyE-site of Bacillus subtilis via double recombination. The two recombination sites flank a standard BioBrick multiple cloning site (with RFP-cassette), as well as a chloramphenicol resistance cassette (5 ??g/ml). The backbone does not contain the restriction sites EcoRI, XbaI, SpeI, PstI, NgoMIV nor AgeI. The vector is replicative in Escherichia coli and provides resistance to ampicillin (100 ??g/ml).
Before transformation into B. subtilis, this vector should be linearized with ScaI.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: This is one of three empty vectors with compatible integration loci and resistance cassettes to allow combination of up to three constructs of choice in one single strain.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: pSB1A3
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: High copy BioBrick assembly plasmid
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty & Tom Knight
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
pSB1A3-1 is a high copy number plasmid carrying ampicillin resistance.
The replication origin is a pUC19-derived pMB1 (copy number of 100-300 per cell).
pSB1A3 has terminators bracketing its MCS which are designed to prevent transcription from *inside* the MCS from reading out into the vector. The efficiency of these terminators is known to be < 100%. Ideally we would construct a future set of terminators for bracketing a MCS that were 100% efficient in terminating both into and out of the MCS region.
A fully annotated Genbank file is attached below.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: pSB3K3

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: pSB3K3-1 is a medium copy plasmid with kanamycin resistance. It has a p15A pMR101-derived replication origin, copy number 20-30. (Lutz and Bujard, 1997) pSB3K3-1 has a terminator upstream of its MCS, which is oriented to prevent transcription from *inside* the MCS from reading out into the vectorl. A second terminator (E.coli His operon-derived) is downstream of the MCS, again insulating the vector from transcription reading out of the MCS. Ideally, future versions of standard biobrick vectors would have terminators bracketing the MCS that were 100% efficient in terminating transcription both into and out of the MCS region.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: To allow the possibility to save some nucleotides of primer-overhangs, you can use this vector. The cassette is flanked by the modified Freiburg standard (http://2012.igem.org/wiki/images/b/b9/LMU-Munich_2012_Our_Freiburg_standard_FusionPrefix.pdf) that includes an optimal ribosome binding site between XbaI and NgoMIV restriction sites.

suffix: ACCGGTTAATACTAGTAGCGGCCGCTGCAGT
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: pSB1C3; the RFP-part is originally from Discosoma sp.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: pSB2K3
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Inducible copy number BioBrick plasmid
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Sri Kosuri
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
pSB2K3 is a variable copy number plasmid carrying kanamycin resistance. The plasmid contains the F' replication origin and also the P1 lytic replication origin. Genes encoding proteins that are required to activate the P1 lytic replication origin are carried on the plasmid under the control of a lacI-regulated promoter. When grown in cells producing LacI the plasmid is maintained at very low copy (<10 per cell). When induced with IPTG the P1 lytic replication proteins are produced and the P1 lytic replication origin takes over, raising the copy number to very high levels (>100++ per cell). The copy control features of pSB2K3 are useful for cloning "difficult" parts while still being able to prepare large amounts of DNA.
Additionally, pSB2K3 has terminators bracketing its MCS which are designed to prevent transcription from *inside* the MCS from reading out into the vector. The efficiency of these terminators is known to be < 100%. Ideally we would construct a future set of terminators for bracketing a MCS that were 100% efficient in terminating both into and out of the MCS region.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
*** pSCANS via BNL ***
The pSB2 series plasmids are based on the pSCANS-5 plasmid from John Dunn's group at Brookhaven National Laboratory. The pSCANS plasmids are introduced here.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: MIT SBWG modification of pSCANS-5 from BNL

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_J64100
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Medium copy ColE1 BioBrick vector
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Jeffrey J Tabor
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This plasmid is based on pProTetE333 (clontech). A SpeI site was removed via an A-T mutation at position 1166 on the original plasmid, resulting in pProTetE333b. The G00100-G00101 fragment of pSB4A3-1 which includes P1010 between a biobricks multiple cloning site which itself is flanked by + strand transcriptional terminators was then cloned between the XhoI and AvrII sites of pProTetE333b. The resulting plasmid carries a ColE1 origin of replication, a Chloramphenicol resistance marker, the biobricks MCS and the ccdAB death cassette.
